I am probably=C2=A0the=C2=A0person in the world who was most susceptible to=
 Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cactually it=E2=80=99s complicated=E2=
=80=9D defense of the collapse of his crypto exchange, FTX Trading:
=09I love for things to be complicated!=09I have, if I do say so myself, a =
pretty robust sense of humor about fraud, particularly crypto fraud.=09I ha=
ve met Bankman-Fried and liked him, and actually   found his arguments abou=
t real-time automated futures margining compelling.=09I have written a lot =
about things =E2=80=94=C2=A0the breakdown in the   nickel market=C2=A0last =
year, the collapse of   Silicon Valley Bank=C2=A0earlier this year =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that have approximately the same=C2=A0shape as the collapse of FTX=
, but=C2=A0without=C2=A0any fraud.

So when SBF   was like =E2=80=9Csee, I was running a leveraged financial in=
stitution that took customer deposits for margin trades and leveraged futur=
es bets; I was doing what I thought was reasonable risk management, but the=
n a once-in-a-lifetime storm crashed the crypto markets and a run on the ba=
nk evaporated my customers=E2=80=99 money,=E2=80=9D I was pretty much the i=
deal audience for that pitch.
Still there were two huge problems with that pitch.   One is that it was no=
t, on its own terms,=C2=A0true. You could imagine a world in which Bankman-=
Fried was right, one where FTX=E2=80=99s=C2=A0terms of service made it clea=
r that he was allowed to reinvest customer money, where FTX=E2=80=99s good-=
faith risk management was overwhelmed by a market crash. It=E2=80=99s just =
that in the actual world none of that was true. The terms of service did no=
t say that,=C2=A0Bankman-Fried was taking insane risks with customer money =
and lying about it constantly, and FTX=E2=80=99s apparently pretty good ris=
k management engine was just=C2=A0turned off=C2=A0when it came to Bankman-F=
ried=E2=80=99s own trading firm, Alameda Research, which took and lost all =
that customer money. Also FTX=E2=80=99s insurance fund that was meant to pr=
otect customer deposits   did not exist; it was just a number displayed=C2=
=A0on a website and produced by a=C2=A0random number generator. Ten seconds=
 after FTX collapsed, it was possible to think =E2=80=9Cwell that happens s=
ometimes at leveraged financial institutions.=E2=80=9D A year later, it was=
 not.
The other, and frankly bigger, problem is that I was not on the jury.=C2=A0=
And for a normal person who does not love financial complexity and have a s=
oft spot=C2=A0for fraud, this case was very very very very very very very s=
imple.=C2=A0Obviously a lot of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0not just Bankman-Fried=
=C2=A0but also the prosecutors, journalists, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0have some =
incentive to make it seem complicated.=C2=A0But all that you actually need =
to tell a jury is:
=09Customers deposited billions of dollars at FTX.=09Bankman-Fried spent a =
whole lot of it on baubles like Bahamas beachfront real estate, political d=
onations, Tom Brady, etc.=09The customers asked for their money back and it=
 wasn=E2=80=99t there.

There is just no coming back from that, you know? Bankman-Fried did not:   =
Last=C2=A0Thursday, after four weeks of trial and less than five hours of d=
eliberation, the jury came back with a verdict of =E2=80=9Cobviously guilty=
,=C2=A0come on.=E2=80=9D Ernest Hemingway famously describes a character go=
ing bankrupt =E2=80=9Cgradually, then suddenly,=E2=80=9D and everyone alway=
s quotes that about every corporate bankruptcy; Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s law=
yer said it about FTX in his closing argument. But it also describes his co=
nviction: The slow accumulation of evidence, the quick and obvious decision=
.
  [1]

There is one more problem with the =E2=80=9Cbank run=E2=80=9D defense: FTX =
was not a bank. Ordinarily, when you run a highly leveraged financial insti=
tution, and it collapses, and you say =E2=80=9Cah well that=E2=80=99s the w=
ay things sometimes go at highly leveraged financial institutions,=E2=80=9D=
 you were running a regulated financial=C2=A0institution. The thing you wer=
e running =E2=80=94=C2=A0a bank, a commodities futures exchange =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0served some social purpose, and the leverage you provided was an esse=
ntial part of that purpose. So regulators allow it, but uneasily: They keep=
 an eye on you, they monitor your risks, they don=E2=80=99t let you lend al=
l of your depositors=E2=80=99 money to one affiliated hedge fund, etc. Ther=
e are rules to keep the customer money safe, and they also serve to keep=C2=
=A0you=C2=A0safe: Sometimes banks blow up, but if you ran your bank accordi=
ng to the rules, you don=E2=80=99t generally go to jail for its failure.
Running a crypto futures exchange in the Bahamas is not like that. It=E2=80=
=99s not that there were no rules, exactly; Bankman-Fried certainly found a=
 lot of rules to break. But there was not a mature regulatory environment, =
and the people running FTX seem to have thought that they could make up the=
 rules as they went. Nor was there much of a social purpose to what Bankman=
-Fried was up to: For all of FTX=E2=80=99s Super Bowl ads urging people to =
get into crypto, Bankman-Fried never really argued that he was doing anythi=
ng useful. FTX was not channeling money from savers into productive busines=
ses. He was providing a casino for crypto gamblers, taking a cut of their m=
oney and using it for=C2=A0effective altruism and marketing.
When it turned out that he was taking, not a cut of their money, but =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0kind of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0all of it, then that just looks like the pu=
rest possible fraud. In happier times, Bankman-Fried once   described to me=
=C2=A0the crypto tokens that his exchange traded with incredible cynicism, =
and I said: =E2=80=9CYou're just like, well, I'm in the Ponzi business and =
it's pretty good.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CI think that=E2=80=99s a pretty reason=
able response,=E2=80=9D he said.) When the Ponzi business collapses, though=
, it=E2=80=99s pretty bad.

