   =20
      BNY Mellon multi-manager
   =20
 =20

Traditionally, the way to be a good hedge fund manager was to be good at pi=
cking investments that would go up. A good track record, and a good story t=
o tell about your track record, were the main things. Possibly the only thi=
ngs: In the olden days, hedge funds were thought of as being less bureaucra=
tic and political than big banks; each hedge fund was a pirate ship run by =
a charismatic captain who cared nothing for social niceties and just maximi=
zed loot.
In modern hedge funds, the dominant model is the multi-manager, multi-strat=
egy =E2=80=9Cpod shop.=E2=80=9D The way to be a good portfolio manager at o=
ne of those funds is=C2=A0also=C2=A0to be good at picking investments that =
go up, subject to more constraints (on risk, factor neutrality, office poli=
tics, etc.) than the traditional pirate manager.
But the way to be a good=C2=A0boss=C2=A0of those funds is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I =
mean, empirically, they tend to be run by people whose training was in inve=
sting. You start a hedge fund, you pick investments that go up, you get big=
, you hire some PMs and become a multi-manager fund. Obviously some skills =
(risk management,=C2=A0knowing which managers will be good) remain importan=
t. But there are new skills involved. The essential jobs are recruiting and=
 retaining and motivating and managing the portfolio managers, giving them =
the constraints and resources that will make them most productive. Also man=
aging the clients. And so the big multi-manager funds, these days, are quit=
e=C2=A0institutional; they have a lot of people doing compliance and human =
resources and recruiting and investor relations. It is=C2=A0more bureaucrat=
ic than it used to be, less of a pirate ship.
Who will be the=C2=A0next=C2=A0big multi-manager fund? Will it be some pira=
te-ship hedge fund manager who has built a good track record as an=C2=A0inv=
estor, and who decides to grow her platform by hiring some portfolio manage=
rs and becoming a pod shop? Will it be some deputy at an existing multi-man=
ager fund who knows how that sausage is made and wants to split off on her =
own? Or will it be a boring bank or mutual-fund manager that is like =E2=80=
=9Cwell, we are pretty good at HR and stuff, and we know all the clients, a=
nd I bet we could charge less=E2=80=9D? The  Financial Times reports:

A $111bn investment boutique owned by BNY Mellon is seeking seed capital fr=
om investors to enter the multi-manager hedge fund business dominated by th=
e likes of US giants Citadel and Millennium.
Mainstream asset manager Newton Investment Management is pitching investors=
 a multi-manager hedge fund with teams trading equities, currencies, commod=
ities, bonds and quant strategies. The talks are still in their early stage=
s and being led by newly appointed deputy chief investment officer for mult=
i-asset, Paul Brain. ...
Newton=E2=80=99s planned hedge fund would seek to replicate the success of =
prominent multi-managers, but at a lower cost than some of the high-profile=
 players in the industry.
=E2=80=9CWe believe the cost of offering this [type of fund] should be lowe=
r,=E2=80=9D said Euan Munro, CEO of Newton Investment Management.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=A6
One allocator of investments to hedge funds questioned if Newton would be a=
ble to attract top talent without charging the high fees of the large multi=
-managers that dominate the industry. =E2=80=9CWe are seeing more and more =
funds switching to the pass through model or increasing performance fees to=
 remain competitive in the compensation game,=E2=80=9D he said.
Newton said that it would still be able to compete for talent with existing=
 multi-managers despite offering lower fees, however.
=E2=80=9CMy experience is that it=E2=80=99s wrong to assume that all talent=
ed [portfolio managers] want to work in a ruthless environment focused on p=
ersonal performance,=E2=80=9D Munro said. =E2=80=9CIn my experience no two =
talented [portfolio managers] are the same.=E2=80=9D

In general, I am very sympathetic to claims like =E2=80=9Cthere are a lot o=
f incredibly talented people who want less stress in their lives, and are w=
illing to take a pay cut to be yelled at less.=E2=80=9D Quite possibly ther=
e is a market opportunity for a Nice Pod Shop, one that pays portfolio mana=
gers less but that attracts top talent by promising not to get on their cas=
e too much if they have a down month. I am not sure how well that pitch wil=
l work with investors though.

 =20
   =20
      People are worried about private credit liquidity
   =20
 =20

I   wrote last month that =E2=80=9Cprivate credit=E2=80=9D as a category fe=
els new and different from the main existing categories of corporate credit=
 (leveraged loans, bonds), but that over time I expect it to converge. (Jus=
t as loans and bonds, which used to have different lenders and uses, have c=
onverged.) I speculated=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Csometime within the next, like, =
three years, I am going to be writing about a story like =E2=80=98Company X=
 is launching a marketplace to allow private credit lenders to trade loans.=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Right now private credit is a fairly=C2=A0illiquid=C2=A0=
asset class, which offers attractive returns in part because you=E2=80=99re=
 getting   an illiquidity premium, but in fairly short order=C2=A0someone w=
ill be like =E2=80=9Cehh I=E2=80=99d rather have the liquidity.=E2=80=9D
Today at Bloomberg, Laura Benitez and Silas Brown   write about liquidity i=
n the private credit market. I mean, they are writing about the liquidity o=
f limited partner stakes in private credit funds, not of the individual loa=
ns, but still:

Buyers including Apollo Global Management, Ares Management and Tikehau Capi=
tal have raised billions to spend on so-called =E2=80=9Csecondary=E2=80=9D =
deals, when an investor in a private credit fund decides to sell their stak=
e early. But in some cases they=E2=80=99re being excluded from lists of app=
roved acquirers by the firms who run the funds, according to people with kn=
owledge of the matter.
While secondary sales have been increasing of late, restricted-buyer lists =
threaten to hobble efforts to make private credit more liquid. Giant insura=
nce and pension firms have been piling into the asset class recently, promp=
ting worries at the Bank of England, European Union and International Monet=
ary Fund about how easily they=E2=80=99d be able to sell out of their expos=
ure in a crunch.
Private credit investors need the consent of a fund=E2=80=99s manager =E2=
=80=94 known as the general partner =E2=80=94 before they can sell their ho=
lding. But some GPs have been reluctant to let close rivals buy stakes beca=
use they fear it would allow them too good a view of the inner workings of =
their portfolios. =E2=80=A6
Although investors understand this asset class is by its nature illiquid =
=E2=80=94 usually involving closed-end vehicles with caps on withdrawals th=
at make private corporate loans =E2=80=94 the promise of a robust secondary=
 market has reassured some that their exposure can be better managed.
The private credit market, which has boomed as investment banks retreated f=
rom the business of lending money to risky companies, is yet to be fully te=
sted in a crisis. And its ability to liquidate holdings is a key danger hig=
hlighted by regulatory bodies such as the EU, whose questions are surfacing=
 just as insurance and pension funds plan to increase holdings in the asset=
 class.

My   view of private credit   continues to be =E2=80=9Cif someone is going =
to be making long-term loans that they have to hold to maturity, it=E2=80=
=99s good for that lender to be a pension fund or life insurer with long-te=
rm funding, and private credit is sort of a jazzy description for that,=E2=
=80=9D but apparently everyone else=E2=80=99s view is more complicated.
Elsewhere, here Marc Rubinstein on private credit. He quotes Apollo=E2=80=
=99s Marc Rowan making the point that one reason for the boom in private cr=
edit is the worsening liquidity in public credit markets:
=E2=80=9CBy some estimates, dealer capital =E2=80=93 the capital that facil=
itates trading =E2=80=93 is roughly 10% today of what it was in 2008.=E2=80=
=9D Yet markets are three times the size. Rowan sees last year=E2=80=99s br=
eakdown in the UK liability-driven investment (LDI) pension industry as the=
 kind of thing that=E2=80=99s inevitable in a less liquid public market. =
=E2=80=9CIt will not surprise me going forward to see liquidity challenged,=
 public markets challenged, and investors beginning to understand that liqu=
idity only exists on the way up and does not exist on the way down,=E2=80=
=9D says Rowan. =E2=80=9CWe should expect a more volatile, less liquid worl=
d in public markets.=E2=80=9D
If you are not happy with bond market liquidity anyway, the illiquidity in =
private credit will be less daunting.

 =20
   =20
      PIK loans
   =20
 =20

Elsewhere in private credit products that work best=C2=A0with long-term loc=
ked-up capital,=C2=A0PIK is back:

Private equity titans are dusting off an old gambit to cope with the rising=
 cost of interest on their leveraged buyout loans: Don=E2=80=99t pay cash.
Instead, they=E2=80=99re making payments with more debt, preserving liquidi=
ty for now with the promise of a bigger payoff later when the debts mature.=
 Those =E2=80=9Cpayment-in-kind=E2=80=9D loans don=E2=80=99t always come ch=
eap =E2=80=94 the annual interest runs as high as 16% =E2=80=94 but lenders=
 and borrowers are wagering that they=E2=80=99ll refinance when rates come =
down long before the due date.
Private equity firms ranging from Carlyle Group Inc., Vista Equity, BC Part=
ners, TPG Inc., Cinven and One Rock Capital Partners are using PIK to buy o=
r refinance companies that otherwise might struggle to carry heavy LBO debt=
. In turn, it=E2=80=99s a boon for direct lenders that offer PIK financing,=
 such as Apollo Global Management Inc. and Ares Management Corp., which get=
 an edge over Wall Street banks because PIK debt is harder to sell in tradi=
tional syndicated markets. =E2=80=A6
They need it, because buyout math is getting harder. With benchmark rates h=
overing near their highest since 2007, an LBO with typical terms and debt t=
hat was easily affordable two years ago could have negative cash flow today=
. That makes PIK an attractive option if the loan is indeed refinanced earl=
y in its life.

The  big story of the last year or so in financial markets has been a rapid=
 increase in interest rates after many years of stable low rates. The parti=
cular dynamic there =E2=80=94=C2=A0everyone got  used to low rates, rates w=
ent up a lot, and everyone was surprised =E2=80=94=C2=A0has had huge impact=
s; among other things it sort of destroyed the crypto market and also blew =
up some regional banks. But now it is, in some sense, over: The rapid unexp=
ected rise has happened, there has been some fallout, and now rates are hig=
her and people at least know that higher rates are a possibility.
But we are now in a period where the big story might be =E2=80=9Ceveryone t=
hinks that high rates are a dream and they will wake up=E2=80=9D? The entir=
e pitch for US residential real estate is =E2=80=9Cbuy a house now, even th=
ough=C2=A0mortgage rates are 8%, and just  refinance for free later when th=
ey go back down to normal.=E2=80=9D But is a 3.5% mortgage rate really norm=
al? Are you so sure that rates are heading back down soon?
Anyway the pitch for leveraged buyouts is apparently the same? =E2=80=9CBuy=
 this company now, even though rates are 16%, capitalize the interest and r=
efinance for free later when rates go back down to normal.=E2=80=9D It will=
 be a mess if they don=E2=80=99t.

 =20
   =20
      Still Sculptor
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CSculptor=E2=80=99s over,=E2=80=9D I   wrote last week: Sculptor Ca=
pital Management Inc.'s deal to sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp., which w=
as in doubt for months due to a higher bid from a group led by Boaz Weinste=
in, finally seems to be done. Rithm raised its bid from $12 to $12.70, stil=
l lower than Weinstein's bid but quicker and more certain, and Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s estranged founder, Dan Och, agreed to vote for Rithm=E2=80=99s deal=
. That means that almost half of Sculptor=E2=80=99s shares (Och=E2=80=99s, =
current management=E2=80=99s, and some shares owned by Rithm) are locked up=
 to vote for the deal, making it very likely to go through. Also Och   had =
filed a pretty punchy lawsuit to stop the deal, and he dropped it last week=
. Also last week,=C2=A0Institutional Shareholder Services recommended that =
shareholders vote for the deal, and said that it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cnearly =
a foregone conclusion=E2=80=9D anyway.
Still  here=E2=80=99s Alison Frankel:

Rithm Capital=E2=80=99s $720 million bid for hedge fund Sculptor Capital Ma=
nagement will be probed at a preliminary injunction hearing in Delaware Cha=
ncery Court on Nov. 14, two days before a scheduled Nov. 16 shareholder vot=
e on the deal. ...
The Sculptor special board committee that led deal negotiations told a Dela=
ware Chancery Court judge that it had received no response from a rival bid=
der =E2=80=93 a consortium of high-profile hedge fund managers led by Boaz =
Weinstein of Saba Capital =E2=80=93 after the Och group threw its 15% votin=
g bloc behind Rithm=E2=80=99s sweetened offer of $12.70 per share.
But at a telephone hearing on Wednesday evening, Vice Chancellor Sam Glassc=
ock said he was not convinced that the Weinstein group was =E2=80=9Cout of =
the picture.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
The judge opened Wednesday evening=E2=80=99s hearing by questioning the nee=
d for a preliminary injunction proceeding in light of Sculptor assertions t=
hat the Weinstein consortium had "withdrawn" from bidding to acquire the he=
dge fund.
But he was apparently swayed otherwise by arguments from shareholder lawyer=
 Ned Weinberger of Labaton Sucharow. =E2=80=A6
Glasscock said on Wednesday that he has =E2=80=9Creal concerns=E2=80=9D abo=
ut the Och group=E2=80=99s conduct. The vice chancellor said he had not rea=
ched any final conclusions about whether the group had damaged other shareh=
olders but ruled that Labaton is entitled to depose Och and to obtain disco=
very from his allies.

Basically Och and his fellow former executives=C2=A0were=C2=A0suing Sculpto=
r to stop the Rithm deal, but are now supporting it. Och=E2=80=99s group ar=
gues that this is because the Rithm deal is now better for all shareholders=
: The group=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cnegotiations with Rithm prodded the real est=
ate investment firm to raise its offer by about $44 million =E2=80=93 a bou=
nty, it said, for all Sculptor shareholders.=E2=80=9D The class-action lawy=
ers, though, argue that Och got some special benefits out of the deal, main=
ly involving Sculptor=E2=80=99s   tax receivable=C2=A0agreement, and that n=
ow everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s board, its management, Och =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is selling out shareholders to get benefits for themselves. =
Also apparently Weinstein is still around willing to pay $13.50. So the dea=
l is not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0done yet.

