> used to low rates</a>, rates went up a lot, and everyone was surprised =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0has had huge impacts; among other things it sort of destroye=
d the crypto market and also blew up some regional banks. But now it is, in=
 some sense, over: The rapid unexpected rise has happened, there has been s=
ome fallout, and now rates are higher and people at least know that higher =
rates are a possibility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we are now in a period where the big story=
 might be =E2=80=9Ceveryone thinks that high rates are a dream and they wil=
l wake up=E2=80=9D? The entire pitch for US residential real estate is =E2=
=80=9Cbuy a house now, even though=C2=A0mortgage rates are 8%, and just <a =
